  "prompt": "How realistic is asking for a 175k base salary, 20% bonus, and 100K in stock per year at a very successful software corporation in the Bay Area (Google), for a computer science PhD (from a top 5 school) for a research-oriented role?",
  "response": "Your ask for a **$175k base salary** + **20% bonus** + **$100k in stock per year** at a prestigious Bay Area tech company like Google for a research-oriented role with a PhD from a top 5 school is **realistic and within the range of what such candidates can expect**, though it may depend on specific factors like your experience, negotiation skills, and the exact role.\n\n### Breakdown of Compensation Components:\n1. **Base Salary ($175k)**:\n   - For a PhD graduate in a research-oriented role (e.g., Research Scientist, Senior Software Engineer), this is within the expected range at top-tier companies like Google. Base salaries for PhD hires in such roles often range from **$150k to $200k**, depending on experience and expertise.\n   - If you have significant industry experience or a strong publication record, pushing toward the higher end of this range is feasible.\n\n2. **Bonus (20%)**:\n   - A 20% target bonus is reasonable for research or engineering roles at Google. Bonuses are typically performance-based, and this percentage aligns with Google\u2019s compensation structure for PhD-level hires in technical roles.\n\n3. **Stock ($100k per year)**:\n   - Stock grants are a key part of compensation at companies like Google. For a PhD hire, **$100k per year in stock (vesting over 4 years)** is realistic. This is often structured as a **$400k grant vesting over 4 years**, which is consistent with what top-tier PhD candidates can expect in research or engineering roles.\n\n### Factors That Influence the Offer:\n1. **Your Experience**:\n   - If you have prior industry experience, internships, or a strong publication record, your leverage to negotiate higher compensation increases.\n   - Fresh PhD graduates with exceptional research output or alignment with Google\u2019s priorities may also secure strong offers.\n\n2. **Role and Level**:\n   - Research Scientist roles (L4 or L5) at Google typically command this level of compensation. If the role is more senior (e.g., L5), the offer could be even higher.\n\n3. **Market Conditions**:\n   - Compensation can vary slightly based on the demand for your skill set, the company\u2019s hiring needs, and broader market trends in the Bay Area.\n\n4. **Negotiation**:\n   - If you have competing offers or can demonstrate your unique value, you may be able to push for a higher base salary, bonus, or stock grant.\n\n### Conclusion:\nYour ask is **realistic and aligned with what top PhD graduates in computer science can expect at Google or similar companies** for research-oriented positions. If you have strong qualifications or multiple offers, you may even negotiate for a slightly higher package. Make sure to emphasize your research impact, technical expertise, and alignment with the company\u2019s goals during the negotiation process.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
